HIV/AIDS: China reports a 14% increase in new cases
China has reported a 14% increase in the number of people infected with HIV and AIDS.
According to health officials, the infection infected more than 820,000 people in the country.
In the second quarter of 2018 alone, about 40,000 new cases were reported.
Most newly infected people have been sexually transmitted, and this is different from past statistics.
Traditionally, HIV infection has spread rapidly in some parts of China due to infected blood transfusions.
But the number of people infected with HIV has fallen to almost zero, Chinese health officials said at a conference in Jun'an province.
However, over time, the number of people living in China with HIV infection and AIDS has increased to 100,000.
Sexually transmitted HIV is a serious issue in the Chinese LGBT community.
Homosexuality in China was decriminalized in 1997, but discrimination against LGBT people is widespread.
As conservative values prevail in the country, 70-90% of men who have sex with men are ultimately married to women.
Most cases of infection with this disease occur due to inadequate protection measures during such sexual intercourse.
Since 2003, the Chinese government has promised universal access to anti-HIV medicines as one way to combat this problem.
