Red flood news: Concentrations in Painelas, Manatia and Sarasota are declining
A recent report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission (FWC) said that the total concentration of the “red flood” in the waters of the Gulf of Tampa is decreasing.
According to the FWC, more fragmented blooms have been observed in the districts of Painelas, Manatis, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, suggesting that concentrations are decreasing.
The bloom of the Red Flood covers approximately 130 miles of coastline from the northern Painelas to the southern Li counties.
Flowering areas can be found about 10 miles from the shore in Hillsboro County, but fewer than last week .
The "red flood" was also observed in Paska district.
Last week it was reported that the concentration in the district of Lianelasa and along its coast is medium, along the coast of Hilsboro county – from low to high, in the district of Manati – from high to high, in Sarasota county and along the coast – from low to high.
There are still reports of respiratory irritation in the districts of Painelas, Manatis, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
There have been no reports of airway irritation in northwest Florida in the past week.
